{"/service/ndnp/njr/batch_njr_basil_ver02/data/sn85035720/00279529935/1908021702/0391.xml":{"full_text":"LARGEST\nCIRCULATION.\nPERTH AMBOY EVENING NEWS.\nVOL. XXVnl. NO. 169. PERTH AMBOY, N. J\u201e MONDAY, FEB. 17,1908\u2014 8 PA1E3 {TEN CENTS A WEEK \u03b9\nLAST\nEDITION.\nTWO CEN'TS.\nWATER BOARD MAJORITY OUSTS\nDEMOCRATS FROM POSITIONS\nNotices Sent to\nTwo at Runyon\nPlantJToday.\nCROWELL MAY\nCET CLERKSHIP\nIt became known thle morning\nthat, when the Board of Water Com\nmissioners held a secret session In\nthe council chamber after the regu\nlar meeting on Wednesday night,\nFebruary 5, at which no newspaper\nmen were allowed, the republican\nmajority In the board decided to oust\nsome of the democratic officeholders\nfrom the department.\nThe first order to this effect was\nsent to Runyon this morning, under\ninstructions from the commissioners,\nby Superintendent Burns to Henry\nMcArdle, an engineer, and Abram\nApplegate, a firemen. 1\nThe matter. It Is said, was brought\nup at the secret meeting just as soon\nas the reporter had been put out.\nThe democratic members objected to\nousting the men, saying that politics\nshould not enter in a case like this,\nand that some of these men had been\nin the employ of the water depart\nment for years.\nMcArdle, who has been In the\nwater works department for some\nyears, worked up from the position\nof fireman, and Is thoroughly ac\nquainted with the work. He Is to be\nsucceeded by Peter Poulsen, of this\ncity. Applegate Is to be succeeded\nby Benjamin Bloodgood, also of this\ncity, who, until recently, was engi\nneer on the county bridge between\nthis city a;nd South Amboy. The\nchanges will take place March 1. I\nThe republican water commission\ners feel also that the work In the\noffice of Superintendent Burns is now\neo heavy that one clerk cannot do It\nand that it is necessary to put on\nanother clerk, and it is rumored that\nA. H. Crowell, the former collector\nof revenue, will be appointed to that\nposition and, In time, if the republi\ncans retain control, he may succeed\nJoseph Burns m superintendent.\nLATE TRAINS ON\nRAPID TRANSIT\nIn addition to the change In sched-l\nule by the Staten Island Rapid Tran-'\nstt railroad on Saturday, two morei\ntrains were added to the time table!\nIssued at that time.\nSpecial notices were posted In the\u00b7\ndepots and ferry houses that theatre'\nspecials would be run. The last\ntrain boat from this city during the\nweek will be at 15 minutes after\nmidnight, connecting with a train\nleaving Tottenville at 12:25. The\nother train is a 1:00 a. m. boat from\nNew York, connecting with a train at\nSt. George at 1:23 a. m., for all sta-j\ntions on the Amboy division, arriving \u03b9\nin this city at 2:18 a. m. 1\nRESTORING THE\nBURNED PLAGES\nThe Insurance companies have\nsettled for the damage to the build\nings along Smith street in the recent\nAre, and repairs will shortly be com\nmenced. The Crouse Construction\nCompany has been awarded the con\ntract on the Timmens building, and\nthis morning started work.\nThe people who occupied the\nbuildings in the block are removing\nthe goods which was not too badly\ndamaged to be of use.\nMEMBERS OF KNIGHTS\nCOLUMBUS AT VESPERS\nThe members of San Salvador\nCouncil No. 299, to the number of\nabout 150, attended solemn vespers\nIn St. Mary's R. C. church at 7:30 j\no'clock last night. They were ad\ndressed by Rev. Father Alexia, of\nthe Monestary at Hoboken. Rev.\nPeter Corr was the celebrant, and\npronounced the benediction. The\nmembers of the council sang the ves\npers. Monslgnor \u0392. T. O'Connell,\nRev. Thomas Massey, of the church,\nand Rev. Father Galassl were in the\nsanctuary during the service.\nChild Wanders \u039b train.\nneniamin Bailey, of Front street,\nfound Helen Young, eight years old,\na colored girl who is in the habit of\nrunning away from home, along\nshore late last night. He took her\nto police headquartei-B, and Patrol- \u03b9\nman Andrew Jensen took her home, 'i\nDR. MENDENHALL'S CHURCH\nCLOSED FOR LACK OF FUNDS\nA notice was posted on the door o(\nthe Westminster Presbyterian church\nin West Twenty-third street, New\nYork, Saturday night that there\nwould be no services In that edifice\nuntil further notice. The pastor Is\nRev. Dr. Harlan G. Mendenhall,\nformer pastor of the First Presby\nterian church In-this city.\nThere has been no money to pay\nthe sexton for some time, and, as the\ntemperature of the church has been\nrather chilly, it has been decided to\nhave no more services, until warmer\nweather, at least.\nTills church has had many difficul\nties ever since the pastorate of Rev.\nJohn Lloyd Lee, and withdrawal\nfrom the Presbytery ot New York\nwas at one time made. The number\nof male members dropped so low that\nsome tnen were holding two offices in\nthe church, which caused a request\nfrom the presbytery to alter the sfc.te\nof affairs.\nRev. Dr. Mendenhall declined to\ndiscuss the finances of the church,\nwhen seen by reporters, but the no\ntice, posted like a seal over the en\ntrance to the Imposing structure, told\na story of its own. Dr. Mendenhall\nhas labored hard to put the church\non a firmer footing, but the task\nproved to be a gigantic one. Friends\nO- the pastor and people who have\nattended for years hope that, with\nwarmer weather, the services may be\nresumed, and interest in the congre\ngation be increased.\nTHREE SUNDAY\nSELLING GASES\nTwo Dry Goods Store Men and\nOne Saloonkeeper Are Accused\nof Violating the Law.\nPATROLMEN MAKE COMPLAINTS\nA charge of one excise violation\nagainst a saloonkeeper and com\nplaints against two local merchants\nwere the results of Investigations\nmade by the police yesterday, but\notherwise the city, according to the\npolice, was closed as tight as a drum.\nPatrolman Meshrow has made a\ncharge against Waldslaw Salwowskl,\nof 306 High Btreet, a saloonkeeper,\nalleging that he was doing business\nyesterday afternoon, while Patrol\nman Wood has complained that he\nnoticed men coming out of the dry\ngoods stores of B. Goldman, at 283\nSmith street, and Weeden Brothers,\nat 225 Smith street. The three may\nbe arranged before Recorder Plckers\nglll tonight at 7 o'clock.\nYesterday afternoon while Patrol\nman Meshrow was oomlng down High\nstreet, near -Wa^-iagton street, he\nheard the clink of glasses in the sa\nloon at 306 High street, and think\ning this rather queer, he investi\ngated the matter. The patrolman\nwent into tl)e place through the back\nway, and walked into the dining\nroom. As he did so, he Says, Ave\nmen walked out of the side door, to\nWashington stret. The patrolman\ndid not know the men, but he con\ntinued his investigation On a table\nin the dining room he found six\nglasses containing beer, he declares,\nand a cooler under the stairs.\nMeshrow asked Salwowskl If he was\ndoing business on Sunday, and the\nlatter said he had been entertain\ning a few friends.\nFor bome time yesterday afternoon\nPatrolman Wood watched a number\nof men enter the stores of Goldman,\nand Weeden, on upper Smith street.\nThey went in empty handed and, he\nsays, came out with bundles. The\npatrolman decided that the places\nwere doing business and flled a com\nplaint against them.\nAbout town yesterday thingB were\nquiet. In some places, where the\nowners have a right to keep the\nshades down and the screens in place,\nbecause they have bowling alleys,\nthey did not take advantage of this,\nbut the screens were down and the\ncurtains up, so that the interior could\nbe plainly seen. Others had the\ncurtains down and screns in such a\nway that one could not look into the\nbarroom.\nPITTSBURG'S FLOOD\nIS NOW SUBSIDING\nSpecial by United Press Wire\u00b7.\nPITTSBURG, Feb. 17\u2014With both\nrivers at the twenty-flve-foot mark\nthis morning and Blowly falling,\nPittsburg's flood of 1908 is passing\niown the Ohio and into hletory.\nWhile no lives were lost It left suf\nfering and distress in its wake. The j\nnonetary loss will run Into the\n:housands.\nCARPENTER SEVERS\nFINGER WITH PLANE\nCarl Sorenson, of East avenue, a\n:arpenter, Saturday morning, sev\nired the end of the first finger on his\nlght hand with a plane, cutting an\nirtery. He was taken to the ofllce\n>f Dr. Q. W. Tyrrell, where the\nvound was dressed.\nAiTcetal on Suspicion.\nSteve Hebov. whom the police\nuspect of a t\u00bb*\u00b0ft at Pardee's, was\nr rested this nooQ. I\nL 1\nCOUPON\nThis coupon wher cut out and handed in at the Evening\nNews office, on or beiore 9 a. m.\nMO*DAY, FEBRUARY 24\nCounts one point in EVENING NEWS contest.\nNAME I\nADDRESS.\n'I ,m I III\u00b7\n1 '\"M'J, \u00e9d \u038e.\"-'\u03af\nTO PAY FIRE\nDEPT. SALARIES\nIncreased Revenue From Saloons\nWill Allow Expenditures With\nout Raising Taxes.\nSOME FOR POLICE AND STREETS\nThe passing of the ordinance,\nproviding for a partly-paid Are de\npartment, on its second and final\nreadings may be taken up by the\nBoard of Aldermen at the regular\nmeeting tonight. At a meeting held\nlast Monday, the ordinance was in\ntroduced and passed on its first read\ning.\nMany of those who were at first\nopposed to a paid department are\nnow of the opinion that it is the best\nidea. One thing that worried tax\npayers was that they feared they\nmight have to pay a large increase\nin taxes.\u00b7\nOn this point, Alderman-at-Large\nVoorhees said today:\n\"For the information of people\nwho favor an Improved fire depart\nment, yet fear an Increase In taxes,\nI would make the following state\nment: Owing to the action of the\nExcise Board in increasing the saloon\nlicenses we .expect an increase in\nrecenue of about $30,000 and favor\nexpending the same as follows:\n$8,000 for police; $8,000 for the\nstreet department: and the balance\nfor an improved fire department.\nAs can readily be seen, this does not\nmean higher taxes.\n\"It simply means,\" continued the\nalderman-at-large, \"that we favor\nusing this Increase in revenue in giv\ning the city better police protection,\nbetter streets, and protection against\nthe most dreaded of the elements\nwhich all thickly populated cities\nhave to contend with, fire.\"\nWhen asked by the reporter if the\nmatter would be taken up again to\nnight, Mr. Voorhees said he was not\nsure.\nSome of the volunteer firemen are\nconfident that the change In the de\npartment will never be made. It is\nunderstood that they have interested\nseveral prominent citizens in the\nmatter who are using their Influence\nagainst a paid department. It Is de\nclared that if the ordinance Is passed\n\u03b7 petition will be circulated opposing\nthe proposed change.\nMEDICAL TEST\nFOR NEW COPS\nCity Physician Dr. M. S. Melnzer\nhae received a copy of the ordinance\nof April 17, 1902, regarding the ap\npointment of uniformed policemen.\nAll applicants muet be examined by\nthe city physician.\nFour or five applicants have al\nready been examined by the city\nphysician. It is understood that\nabout a hundred have been examined\n\u03b9 by other physicians, who found them\nineligible.\nVOORH\u00cb\u00cbSlS\nUNDER BONDS\nSpecial by United Pree\u00bb Wire\nNEW YORK. Feb. 17:\u2014Foster\nM. Voorliees, former governor of New\nJersey, and Frank J. Combes, uefore\nJustice Dowling, today, were admit\nted to $2,500 bail each to answer in\ndictments charging them with per\njury In statements made In 904 In\nreports concerning the Bankers' Life\nInsurance Company, of which they\nwere treasurer and secretary. re\nepeetively.\nONE FRENCH AUTOIST\nIS OUT OF THE TOUR\nPHILADELPHIA, Feb. 17:\u2014Left\nbehind by his comrades, M. Lelou\nvier, one of the original members of\nthe French motoring team making\nan Independent trip from New York\nto Paris, threatens to prevent his\ncomrades from accomplishing their\nJourney.\nLast of Sell Bros. Is Dead.\nSpecial by \u00a37tilled Pre\u00bb* Wire:\nNBW YORK, Feb. 17:\u2014William\nBell, the last of the three \"Sell\nBroe.,\" so lon\u00ab prominent as elf-\u2014\nmen, died today from gastritis.\nMORSE SAYS\nNOT GUILTY\nWas Arranged in Court Before\nJustice Dowling Today\u2014Bail\nFixed at $20,000,\nALL WILL BE RIGHT\nWas Arrested When His Vessel\nReached Quarantine Yesterday\n-Taken to Justice's House.\nNEW YORK, Feb. 17.\u2014Charles W.\nMorse, financier and promoter of many\nlarge combination\u00b7, Including the so\ncalled Ice trust and a merger of nearly\nall of tbo coaitwlee steamihlp Hues,\nreturning from his brief trip to Eu\nrope, was arrested In hie stateroom\nwhen the steamer Etrurla reached\nquarantine In the lower bay, held in\ncustody until the ship was docked\nand then was whirled away In an au\ntomobile to the home of Justice Victor\nDowllng of the supreme court, where\nhe gave bond In the sum of $20,000 to\nanswer to two Indictments charging\ngrand larceny and Involving the sum\nof $100,000.\nMr. Morse today appeared before\nJustice Dowllng In open court and\npleaded not guilty to the indictments.\nHe denied that his trip to Europe\nwas a \"flight.\" He said he had gone\nabroad to sell stock in a large Interest\nand to secure a fortnight's rest. Both\npurposes were spoiled by the publica\ntion of reports that he was a fugitive\nfrom Justice, be declared.\nThe financier based bis defense upon\nthe claim that there was no criminal\nIntent in the act for which he was In\ndicted.\nMr. Morse had received word by\nwireless telegraphy that two Indict\nments had been found against him,\nbut he did not know he was to suffer\nphysical arrest. The appearance of\nthree detectlvee from District Attor\nney Jerome's office at his stateroom\ntook him completely by surprise.\nThe charge against Mr. Morse grow\u00b7\nout of a note for $100,000 given to\nhim by former Chief Juetlce Morgan\nJ. O'Brien of the court of appeals.\nMr. Morse declared that he was\n\"feeling fine\" and after he had con\nsulted with his counsel exclaimed:\n\"Well, if that's the worst they hav\u00b7\ngot on me I am not worried.\"\nMr. Morse laughed heartily when one\nof the newspaper men told him It was\nreported that on the way over he had\ncapitalized an Iceberg, had sold the\nbonds to the captain, taken notes In\npayment, discounted them with the\npurser, had bought the Etruria and\nstarted on a cruise around the world.\nMr. Morse said:\n\u038a had two purposes In going to En\nrope. I thought that X might be able\nto sell In England property to which\nI had a large Interest and thus In\ncrease ray ability to meet the claims of\nmy creditors, and I greatly needed a\nfortnight's rest.\n\"By business purpose was of course\ndefeated by the publication In the\nEnglish papers that I was regarded in\nNew York as a fugitive from justice.\nI had straightened out my financial\naffairs when I left New York, so that\nthere were no actions pending against\nme except one brought by a creditor to\nwhom I had given valuable collateral\nsecurities, and I was Informed by my\ncounsel that he had arranged with\nthis creditor not to press his suit\nagainst me.\n\"I had no knowledge that District\nAttorney Jerome contemplated taking\nany proceedings against me, and I\ntherefore did not communicate with\nhim on this subject. About six weeks\nbefore I left New York, hearing that\nUnited States District Attorney Stim\nson was considering the evidence lit\ncertain transactions between the Na\ntional Bank of North America and\nmyself with a view of the possible\npresentation thereof to the federal\ngrand Jury, I asked him on the tele\nphone that I be given an opportunity\nto explain these transactions before\nany indictment was found against me.\nI subsequently wrote to the United\nStates district attorney to the same\neffect.\n\"Not having heard from Mr, Stimson\nin reply to my request for several\nweeks, I naturally reached the conclu\nsion that he had completed his ex\namination and had found nothing\nagainst me. I therefore saw no ob\njection to my short European trip\nbased upon the possibility of criminal\nproceedings against me, either in the\nstate or federal courts.\n\"I did not sail In the Campania un\nder an assumed name and made no\neffort to conceal my identity. The sug\ngestion has been made that I assumed\nthe name of 'C. M. Moore.' My sig\nnature looks as much like \u038c. M. Moore*\nas it does like 'C. W. Morse.'\n'On Friday I decided to sail in the\nCampania and sailed at about 7 o'clock\nSaturday morning. Until I read In the\nEnglish papers that I was traveling\nunder an assumed name I did not\nknow that my name was not correctly\nentered-on the \u00abm\u00abv\u00ab It was\n\n(Continued on page 7J\nANNUAL\nMASKED BALL\nOF\nPo Ambo Haymakers\nASSO. NO. \u03b2\u03b2\u039c\nWashington Hall\nFebruary 18,1908\nBILCRAV UNABLE TO CONTINUE\nHIS BAREFOOT WALK TO PHILA.\nDENMARK'S FINANCIAL PANIC\nIS ENDED BV GOVERNMENT\nRumor\u00b7 of a financial panic In\nDenmark which have come to thle\ncountry recently have caused no little\nanxiety among the Scandinavian resi\ndents In thl\u00b7 vicinity. The NEWS\nlearns, through J. P. Holm, the\nDanish vice consul here, that the\nflurry 1* over and business is resum\ning it\u00b7 normal condition.\nAccording to Mr. Holm, there were\ntwo banks that had trouble. They\nwere the Orundejer bank with a\ncapital of (5,000,000, and the Detail\nhander bank with a capital of\n13,600,000. Contrary to some re\nporta regarding the affair, the Land\nmand\u00b7 bank, one of the largeit, hav\ning a capital ot $20,000,000, was\nnot Involved.\nAs soon as there was a sign of a\nrun on the banks that were hit, the\nFolketlnget, or Danish Congress, on\nthe recommendation of the minister\nof finance, Immediately guaranteed\nthe deposits In both Institutions.\nThis satisfied the people at once, the\ngovernment assumed all responsibil\nity and the trouble ended.\nThe Landmand's bank Is one of\nthe strongest financial Institutions in\nthe world. It has branches in all\nthe Scandinavian countries and many\nof that race In America are deposi\ntors there.\nICE DAMAGES\nAMBOY BRIDGE\nSeven Piles Already Broken by\nHeavy Floes-Ice Wedged\nAgainst Structure.\nLIGHTER HAD NARROW ESCAPE\nIce has begun it\u00b7 work on the\nAm boy bridge. The recent thaw\ncaused a genera] breaking-up up the\nriver and the floee have come down\nthe stream with great force. It was\ndiscovered this morning that several\npiling have already been carried\naway on the north side of the draw\nand much of the ice is still to pass\nout.\nSeven plies are broken, and It is\nfeared that the ice wedged against\nthe bridge may do more damage.\nEarly this morning It was feared\nthat the Ice might damage a lighter\nbelonging to the Merritt-Chapman\nWrecking Company, and Representa\ntive George Hardlman hastened to\nthe scene and had the lighter moored\nIn a safe place.\nThe boat house of the New Bruns\nwick Boat Club was badly damaged\nduring the freshet Saturday by being\nshoved on to a pile which rammed a\nbig hole In the bottom of the scow\non which the house stands. The re\nsult was that when the freshet pass\ned out, the scow settled and the\nhouse was badly warped.\nFARMERS HAVE\nFIRE MYSTERY\nSpecial to the *T EN ISO KBWB:\nNEW BRUNSWICK, Feb. 17:\nSeveral Area In the southern end of\nthe county have greatly excited the\ncountry district today.\nBetween 9 and 10 o'clock last\nnight all the outbuildings on the\nfarm belonging to the Woodbridge\nStrong estate, situated on the Day\nton-Rhode Hall road and occupied by\nEmerson Berdlne, were burned. Two\nhorses, one cow end a calf aleo per\nished.\nAbout 3 o'clock this morning a\nbarn on Michael Heffren's farm on\nthe Friendship road near Dayton\nwas burned. When the farmers\ngathered In an effort to extinguish\nthe flames, it was discovered that a\nhorse, buggy and one set of harness\nwere missing. Two hours later the\nhorse returned home badly used up,\nhaving on It the harness. A search\nwas made and the wagon was found\nIn a woods about a half-mile away,\nsmashed to kindling wood. It is sup- j\nposed the rig was stolen and the barn\n\u00bbet on lire to hide the crime, but that\nthe horse got away from the thieves, j\nWHEELING HAS\nGREAT FLOOD\n9p\u00abo<aI by United Pratt Wire\nWHEELING, W. Va., Feb. 17:\u2014\nWith 7,000 persons driven from their\nlomes, railroad communication al\nDost completely cut off and business\nluspended, and damage wrought to\n:he extent of many thousands of dol\nars, Wheeling today Is suffering a\nHost disastrous flood. Street car\nservice has been cut off and all in\nluetrial plants are Idle. It is be\nieved It will be the middle of the\nveek before normal conditions can\n)e restored.\nTWICE INJURED BY\nA BURSTING BOTTLE\nFrank Staaf, who keeps a bottling\nsstablishment In Penn street, was In\nured Saturday when a soda water\n>ottle which he was filling burst and\nait him in the right hand. An artery\nvas severed. He was taken to the\nifflce of Dr. G. W. Tyrrell. Only a\nihort time ago, Staaf was badly cut\nin the head in a similar manner.\nDIDN'T SEE GLASS;\nWALKED INTY DOOR\nA man tried to enter N. Jacobson's\nlothing store, at 316 State street,\nlaturday afternoon, without opening\nhe door, and was cut about the face,\nike glass waa so clean that it ap\neared aa though the door was open.\nCONTESTANTS\nARE REWARDED\nThree More Persons Receive $5\nEach Today\u2014A oiher Con\ntest is On.\nAN \"EXTRA COUPON\" THIS WEEK\nThere were elx contestants for the\nEVENING NEWS' cash prizes last\nweek. The three highest were Mrs.\nMatilda Pederson, 132 Gordon street,\n1221, points; A. Hansen, 91 High\nstreet, 903 points and Edward Mul\nlln, 19 William street, 529 points.\nThe others in the race were: Miss\nM. 9. Anderson, 228 Market street,\n440; Andrew Jensen, 114 Sayre ave\nnue, 335, and T. Smith, 5 Brodhurst\nplace, 310.\nThe wlnnere get $5 each. It Is a\npretty easy way to get a neat sum\nIn cash every week by hustling for\nsubscribers for the NEWS, and clip\nping the coupons that are published\nevery day. Anybody can do it and\ncan repeat the process as often as\nthey desire. Mrs. Peterson, it will\nbe noticed, has been among the three\nleaders every week since the contest\nstarted. The NEWS has given her\n15 every Monday. What one can do\nothers can do.\nAnother contest Is started today\nand during the week another of thoee\n\"extra coupons\" will be run, each\none of them counting ten points in\nBtead of one. These coupons figure\na whole lot in reaching the total.\nYour neighbors will gladly save them\nfor you for the asking. The sub\nscriptions count as follows: One year,1\n500 pointe, six months, 200 points:\nthree months. 100 points; and one\nmonth, twenty-five points.\nGet busy. Any boy or girl can\nget $5 by a little work after school.;\nWatch for the \"extra coupon\" come \u03b9\nthis week. It will count ten points.\nGet as many on that day as possible.\nStart at once. The contest closes\nnext Monday at 9 o'clock.\nMARRIED ON\nTRIP ARROAD\nJens M. Sorenson, a local painting\ncontractor, who was one of the re\nturning passengers on the steamer\nHelllg Olav, is receiving congratula\ntions on his marriage while on Den\nmark.\nHe left here about two months\nago with a party of four who were\nto visit various places. On January\n29 they were married at the home\nof the bride. Immediately afier the\nwedding they started on a lengthy\nwedding tour throughout Denmark.\nHe brought his bride to this city,\nwhere they will take up their resi\ndence. They expect soon to occupy\na new home of their own. Mrs. Sor\nenson was formerly Miss Olga Frlls.\nADDITION IS READY\nFOR NEW STEEL CELLS\nThe work of completing the new\naddition to city hall, as far as Con\ntractor Walter Quackenboss Is con\ncerned, was finished this morning\nind the painters expect to complete\nIhelr part tonight and Andrew An\nJerson, who Is doing the electrical\nwork, promises that the lights will\nbe burning tonight.\nThe aldermen were to have In\nspected the place Saturday afternoon\nbut as It was not quite ready for\nthem, the inspection was postponed.\nSUES FOR $10,000 FOR\nKILLING OF HUSBAND\nMarlane Lalelund, administratrix\nit the estate of John Ladelund, who\nwas killed by a machine operated by\nthe Pennsylvania railroad company\nIn South Amboy, has, through Law\nyer Henry W. Kehoe, commenced suit\n\u03af\u03bf recover $0,000 damages.\nA settlement had about been reach\n9 few days ago, But the amount of\nfered was not sufficient.\nRUDDER IS STOLEN\nFROM JENSEN'S LAUNCH\nJohan Jensen has reported to the j\n>ollce that on Saturdav afternoon \u03b9\niome one stole a bronre rudder from,\nlie gasoline launch. He offers a re\nrand of (10.\nForced to Quit at\nKingston by\nSore Feet.\nREMARKABLE\nNERVE SHOWN\nI After walking from this city, la\nhie bare feet, to Kingston, about tout\nmiles from Princeton. Peter Bllgrav,\nwho left here Saturday morning on a\nwager that he could walk from thle\ncity to Philadelphia barefooted In\nseventy-four hours, was compelled to\ngive up. He returned to his home\nyesterday by trolley because his feet\nwere swollen and bleeding and that\nhe had walked a great distance la\nthe wrong direction.\nBllgrav is now resting up at hi\u00b7\nhome, 203 Elm street, and when seen\nby a NEWS reporter, this morning,\nihe said he felt all right, but that hi\u00b7\nfeet hurt. He was accompanied all\nthe way by Peter Damm and Han\u00ab\nMeiater, who wore out two pairs of\nshoes on the trip and were compelled\nto purchase new footwear.\nBllgrav, accompanied by Damm\nand Meister, left the Carstensen\nCafe, 112 Fayette street, at promptly\n8:08 o'clock Saturday morning and,\nas rain was falling, It was only a\nshort time before they were wet to\nthe skin. They went from here to\nFords, where they met a man who\ntold them that If they took a certain\nroad to New Brunswick they would\nfind the walking good. They took\nthis road and it was in the worat\ncondition possible and the goirg waa\nso bad that when tUev reached Ne*\nBrunswick, shortly after 1 o'clock,\nBilgrav's feet were sore and it wae\nnecessary for Damm nad Meister to\npurchase new shoes.\nThe party had dinne. at Highland\nPark and at 1:30 o'clock the trip\nwas resumed. At 6:45, they were\nwithin four miles of Kingston, and.\nwhen they reached there, they put\nup for the night. Bilgrav's feet were\nin a bad way and again Damm and\nMeister had to buy new ehoee. Dar\ning the trip from New Brunswick\nto Kingston the men went in the\nwrong direction and lost considerable\ntime and were greatly tired out.\nYesterday morning Bilgrav was in\nbal shape and could not continue, eo\nthe trio boarded a trolley car for\nTrenton. From Trenton they came\nto this city, arriving here about 2\no'clock yesterday afternoon.\nDamm said this morning that he\nfelt no ill effects from his Journey\nand that he could walk from here to\nPhiladelphia, with shoes on, at any\ntime. The money will be returned\nto Kaas and Damm, as it is claimed\nthat Bilgrav lost it by failing to\nwalk to Philadelphia, but some talk\nis heard about presenting him witlx\na purse for the nerve which he dis\nplayed in walking as far as he did.\nGARBAGE SITES\nBADLY NEEDED\nThe question of providing grounds\nfor the garbage of this city Is be\ncoming 6erious, as nearly every place\n\u25a0which has been used, Is filled to Its\ncapacity.\nThe garbage is now being dumped\nat the old Second street site, and\nthere it accumulates so rapidly that\nit le left in heaps. Health Inspector\nBrewster says that It Is difficult for\nwagons to go over the place, and, at\ntimes, even the street is blocked.\nIt has been suggested by the health\nauthorities that a man be stationed\npermanently at the grounds to direct\nthe men where to do the dumping\nand to have them level it \u03bf\u03af\u0393 after\nthe wagons have been emptied.\nThe matter will be brought before\nthe street commissioner at once.\n35 YEARS\" WED;\nWANT DIVORCE\nSpecial to the pvg.vrvfl K\u00cfWS:\nNEW BRUNSWICK. Feb. 17:\u2014\u00b7\nWilliam Arrowsmith, of Browntown,\nhas brought stilt for divorce asainsi\nhis wife, Susan Arrowsmith, alleging\ndesertion. The hearing is on today\nbefore Vice Chancellor Walker.\nThe couple were married at Mata\u00bb\nwan, January 22, 1873. They have\nthree sons, Byron, Wood and Rich\u00bb\nard, all of age. In 1903 Arrowsmith\nsold his farm to his eon Wood and\nmoved to Browntown. He declare\u00b7\nhis wife refused to accompany him,\npreferring to remain in the old\nhomestead with her eon.\nIn her reply to the charge. Mrs.\nArrowsmith claims her husband\nabused her all her married life, forc\ning her to take In washing and do\nother work and that she endured it\nfor the sake of her family.\nArrowsmith is represented by Alan\nH. Strong and his wife Is defended\nby C. T. Cowenhoven.\n\u00bb\u038a\u03bd\u03b2 Members.\nAt the Presbyterian Christian\nEnaeavor Society meeting last night\nfive new members were received.\nMASON SMITH\nCivil Engineers end City Purveyors\nNEW CITY HAPS FOR SALE\n102 Smith Street. Tel. 42 L\n\u00e2ui\u00c9\u00e2","height":"26740","width":"20080"}}
